[recto] Bruegel: Woman Taken in Adultery. Partly indebted to woodcut of the same subject in [Christoph] Froschauer's German bible by Heinrich Vogtherr, ZÃ¼rich, 1545, (repr. James STRACHAN, Early Bible Illustrations. [A Short Study Based on Some Fifteenth and Early Sixteenth Century Printed Texts], Cambridge [University Press], 1957, fig. 94 (see text of Strachan, p. 57f.). This Bible to be looked up for other subjects as well, e.g. Wise & Foolish Virgins, B.M. C. 18.c.3. Bruegel borrowed from Vogtherr the unsual group of the soldiers on the right and among them in particular the first one; [verso] walking towards the [sic], turning his head towards the centre & looking back. The lower part of the Christ armour of Vogtherr's first soldier reappears (slightly altered) in Bruegel's second soldier.
